		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Would people ever stop developing for older consoles?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />While it's true that the majority of NES enthusiasts are motivated by nostalgia, this isn't always the case. I believe that everything that was once relevant will not die easily. Take music for example: a lot of people still like artists that aren't around anymore, even if they weren't born when said artists were active. People still cover their songs and are inspired by them. Significant things are hard to forget, and are always around one way or another.<br /><br />Sure, there will obviously be a decrease in the number of NES homebrews as people who grew up with it &quot;retire&quot; or die, but as long as computers are here, games will exist, programmers will exist, and old consoles are a big part of computing and gaming history, so the NES is sure to get some attention from a few intrigued programmers at least.<br /><br />Not everyone is exclusively interested in the present... There are a lot of people today researching old civilizations and using old techniques to build or create things, for research or even for fun.<br /><br />The hardware will probably be gone not too long from now, but many people are working hard to document everything as well as possible and preserve all the software, so we can at least count on emulation or simulation. I really expect computers in the not-so-distant future to be able to run simulations of electronic circuits fast enough to run a perfect replica of the old consoles in real time.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


