		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">While it's true that the majority of NES enthusiasts are motivated by nostalgia, this isn't always the case.</div><br />Hell, I got my NES only two years ago when I bought mine on eBay. I actually got my SNES when I was four, and lost it (I know that sounds crazy) shortly after and I ended growing up with the N64 (that my cousin gave me, regrettingly) and the GameCube. I guess you could say that I have &quot;nostalgia&quot; for the SNES (even though, like I said, I lost it in my garage and found it when I moved many years latter) but I only really got to play it about three years ago. I honestly just find older games a bit more enjoyable, due to the fact that they don't feel like they drag on forever, and there's no tutorials or cut scenes or those idiotic quick time events to break up the pace. I feel it takes me about as much time to complete an SNES game as it does to complete and Xbox 360 or one or whatever game, not because it's as long, but because I don't feel like I can blaze through everything on my first try. (Beating R-Type III the first time for me was literally a 3-day event, even though you can easily beat the game in an hour.) One thing I really like doing stuff on the SNES is that it really doesn't look that bad (I'd say it's aged 10x better than the original PlayStation's 3D titles) even for today, and I'm not counting looking &quot;retro&quot; but legitimately alright. From what I've heard, its the perfect balance of looks and programming simplicity for a 2D based system.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The hardware will probably be gone not too long from now</div><br />Why? I understand that nothing lasts forever, but what would really go? It's not like it has any moving parts that could cause wear and tear. The only thing I can think of, on the original NES, id the cartridge slot not working, even though from what I heard, they weren't very well built to begin with. My NES is in fine condition (even though I have to wiggle the cartridge around a little to get the game to start sometimes) and there is not a thing wrong with my SNES. It's really a shame how bad the condition of some SNESs I've seen. I don't even really try that much to preserve my SNES, but it doesn't even have the slightest bit of yellow on it. It even still has the sticker that says &quot;<em>POWER SWITCH MUST BE TURNED OFF BEFORE LOADING OR REMOVING A GAME PAK</em>&quot;

		

		</td>
