		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Espozo wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Hell, I got my NES only two years ago when I bought mine on eBay.</div><br />I'm on the same boat. I had an Atari 2600 when I was 5, didn't play video games for a while, and got a Genesis on my 10th birthday. I have zero nostalgia for the NES, I even used to make fun of the kids who were still playing 8-bit games when I owned a cutting edge 16-bit console.<br /><br />Years later I developed an interest for the aesthetics of 8-bit games in general, but when I studied a little bit about how these consoles worked I became fascinated with the NES, even though I never owned one. I did have a Game Boy Pocket and a Master System, both purchased after the Genesis, and for whatever reason I wasn't as interested in them.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The hardware will probably be gone not too long from now</div><br />Why? I understand that nothing lasts forever, but what would really go? It's not like it has any moving parts that could cause wear and tear.</div><br />Old consoles fail all the time. Controllers and cartridge slots frequently become worn out, capacitors go bad, power issues fry chips... all sorts of things.<br /><br />Also, TVs are progressively eliminating support for old video standards, because the future is digital. Soon they won't have RF or composite inputs, forcing people who own old consoles to buy expensive converters, which will also vanish eventually.<br /><br />Some enthusiasts are building modern versions of some old consoles, but the cost of producing those is very prohibitive, and as the number of people interested in such consoles decreases, they won't be economically viable anymore.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


