	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Just my two cents: My favorite musical instrument is the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clavichord" class="postlink">clavichord</a>, which is first known to have appeared in the early 14th century. It's the predecessor to the piano and it still has a following today. Quite small and obscure, but I'd say there are perhaps several thousand people worldwide who appreciate its virtues. I suspect old video game consoles will have a similar fate. To me, old video games have a timeless, almost mythical value to them, much like old books, or old music. It seems every creative era starts out with things that are simple, constrained, and symbolic. It makes me wonder if humanity's gradually evolved tendency to communicate in symbols means that every time a new creative medium is invented, the first masterpieces made in that medium will always be the most highly regarded, because inevitably successors in a given medium will increase the complexity to the point where that deeply innate tendency to respond to simplicity is eroded.<br /><br />I'm hoping to still be playing the clavichord, and writing games for the NES til I'm too old to see or hear, hahahahah.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
