	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>GradualGames</b> [ Tue Feb 10, 2015 9:53 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Would people ever stop developing for older consoles?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Sik wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"> The only reason to develop on an old system is to see if you can get it working with the real constraints being enforced.<br /></div><br /><br />I can't speak for others, but that's not why I do it. It's part nostalgia, but partly because it is a really nice foil against modern software development. In other words, it is really nice to feel like you're building a whole world from the ground up, without depending on fifty github projects, ten browsers, stack overflow, google, and ISP providers all at once. Plus, the NES is so widely emulated, that any game you make is likely to work 50 years from now just because of the strong historical interest there will be in keeping emulators up to date. Make a game for the PC, and the ever changing landscape of languages and open source libraries will likely require significant effort to keep working for that long. I could be wrong, maybe C/SDL (for example) will allow code to run 50 years from now without any modification, but I doubt it...seems much more likely that would be true for the NES, whose requirements are totally solidified and cannot change, the only requirement is that when more emulators are written, that the system emulation itself behaves exactly the same.<br /><br />Tangential: (no pun intended...see the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clavichord" class="postlink">clavichord</a> wikipedia article <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br />As for emulating a clavichord with a synthesizer, one typically encounters the &quot;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clavinet" class="postlink">clavinet</a>,&quot; which is not a clavichord but a modern electric equivalent, which is essentially a keyboard attached to an electric guitar, doing &quot;hammer ons&quot; for each note. A real acoustic clavichord is based on the same principles but sounds and feels much different. I've only ever heard a clavichord sound on a synthesizer once, and it wasn't remotely like the real thing. For instance, you can make any note have vibrato just by bouncing the key. Most synths have a wheel for doing vibrato, which is much more constrained as to what you can do with it. Maybe some synths have pressure sensitive keys that could emulate vibrato, but even then it won't be the same. The quiet acoustics of the instrument would be nearly impossible to emulate properly. Plus, it's fun to feel the string vibrate directly through the key you have depressed, as when you hold down a key it is actually in contact with the string on the other end. There's just nothing like it.<br /><br />Back on topic:<br />My sincere hope is the NES (and other systems and games from the era) will still be valued many many years from now. Maybe I'm wrong but I don't see why interest in something as old and irrelevant to modern culture as the clavichord isn't enough evidence that this phenomenon can occur with almost anything.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


