		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">zzo38 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">GradualGames wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">In other words, it is really nice to feel like you're building a whole world from the ground up, without depending on fifty github projects, ten browsers, stack overflow, google, and ISP providers all at once. Plus, the NES is so widely emulated, that any game you make is likely to work 50 years from now just because of the strong historical interest there will be in keeping emulators up to date.</div>These are some of the main reasons I like it too, actually.<br /><br />(Also remember: Plain TeX will continue working forever. At least, this is what I believe. Like you say a game you make for NES/Famicom is likely to work 50 years from now, similar to how I would think that a document written in Plain TeX will continue working 100 years from now.)</div><br /><br />It turned out to be a wise decision to choose NES for building games, already, even in a much smaller timespan than we are discussing. In 2007 or so I had considered creating Nomolos on XNA for the XBox 360 and windows. However, I knew I couldn't quit my day job or otherwise arrange my relatively balanced life so that I could kill myself over it to get it in the store before the technology changed, so I picked the NES. Sure enough, not long after I finished Nomolos for the NES Microsoft announced they were not supporting XNA anymore. Sure, if I had done it for that platform I could port it, but...it's hard enough for me to find time to build the games, period. Having a platform like the NES that is required to never change is perfect if you want to do a game programming hobby but not have it consume your entire lifestyle. Throw in that I grew up with the system, my favorite games are on it, I'm a huge fan of 8 bit music, and it makes it even more of an obvious choice (for me)

		

		</td>
	</tr>
